  <h2>What is Drop D?</h2>
  <p>
    Drop D lowers only the thickest string — from E down a whole step to
    <strong>D</strong> — while the other five strings stay in standard tuning.
    The result: D–A–D–G–B–E. Power chords become one-finger shapes and the low
    end gets heavier, which is why Drop D shows up everywhere from folk to
    metal.
  </p>
  <h2>How to get to Drop D</h2>
  <p>
    Start from standard tuning, tap start above, and pluck the low E string.
    The tuner will show the peg to use and tell you the pitch is too high —
    loosen that peg slowly until the needle centers on D. The other strings
    shouldn't need to move; pluck each one to confirm.
  </p>
  <p>
    Coming back to standard? Use the <a href="/">standard guitar tuner</a> and
    tighten the low string back up to E.
  </p>
</TunerPage>
